 it known at once. Ad\nvertise in your city daily and get re\nsults.\nTHE WENATCHEE DAILY WORLD, WENATCHEE, WASHINGTON. TUESDAY', MARCH 10, 1908.\nTHEY MY\n\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014i\nI That a street fakir has been selling\n\"Eternity Glue\" on the avenue for\nthe last two or three days;\nj It has been suggested that a few\napplications of this might cement to\njgether the warring political factions\n:a Wenatehee.\nThat the city council, which, owing\nto social hilarities, was too tired to J j\nbusiness last Tuesday, will meet iv\nregular session tonight.\nThat the mayor has under advise\nment a plan for enforcing a genera!\nspring clean-up of backyards and al\nleys.\nThe council tonight will also dis\ncuss the question of the Closet Per\nmit, asked for by the G. N. Ry. Co.\nAn effort will be made to clear\nup the apparent contradictions which\nexist, and come to an understanding.\nThat the return of Prosperity to\nWenatehee has disbanded the Hungry\nClub.\nThat a San Francisco actor has\nbeen arrested for holding up and rob\nbing a pedestrian.\nHis manager has held up a whole\naudience every night for six weeks\nand is still at iarge.\nThat five men are in the field for\ngovernor of this state; it is signifi\ncant that too many politicians cannot\ndistinguish between a call TO an\noffice and call EY an office.\nThat the Asiatic Dragon is angrily\nlashing its serrated tail and the Big\nNoise at Washington is impatient to\nmediate.\nThat a herd of runaway cayuses\nkept three vaqueros busily chasing\nthem up and down the city streets\nfor over an hour yesterday.\ni At one time the stampeding mus\ntangs nearly crashed through the\nplate glass into the Chewawa Bar.\nThey were finally corraled by half\n'a hundred men and boys.\ni The Chicago Record says that some\nI people are so fastidious that when\nI Opportunity knock's they want her to\nsend in an engraved card.\nA news dispatch tttia morning says\nthe Railroad Commission is broke\u2014\ngot no money.\nI This should undeceive the manifold\ncroakers who have maintained that\nj the commission is in the pay of the\nI railroads.\nThat on Easter morning the We\nnatehee police will appear wearing\ncauliflower and other local flora in\ntheir new helmets.\nThar the Pullman company\nseil no more booze upon its cars: thus\nis another hardship of travel removed\n\u2014the booze they sold was awful.\nThat, many officeholders will re\nceive a consignment of lemons on fail\ndelivery.\nCashmere Clippings.\nI A pleasant social evening was\n1 passed Tuesday evening at the resi\ndence of William Paton by the Pres\ni byterian people at an aid social.\nThe M. W. also reproduced ih3ir\nplay \"The Old Dairy Hom\u00abs:.ead,\" on\nthat evening.\nThe school election Saturday\naroused more than a little ordinary\ninterest, over 200 voting for direc\ntors, which shows that soir 5 people\nbegin to realize that ther.> is some\nthing to be done by the genera} pub\nlic in the interest of the\nMr. Prentis and Mr. were\nj re-elected and Grant Paton is the new\nImember of the board.\nMrs. Chas. Hinton, who has been\nj seriously ill. is improving.\nThe children are picking butt ir\ncups on the hills one side of town.\nwhile the hills on the other side are\nI covered with snow.\nMrs. C. I. Curtis is intending to\n'spend the summer In Marshalltown.\nlowa, where she was recently called\n:on business.\nThe services in St. Luke's Episcopal\nchurch will be conducted by laymen\nand the members of the choir. It is\nhoped thai confirmed members and\nI any o!hers who desire will -endeavor\nito attend these Lenten services, The\nI Bishop is considering extending a call\n\u25a0to a clergyman in Pennsylvania.\nplace\u2014Gem Cafe. Yon pay for what\njyou eat; not for style.*-\nThe son or Mr.\nand Mrs. Hohson. who live on Mission]\njured his back while vaulting the polej\nwith his schoolmates.\ni\nSpecial for one week\u2014so calling j\ncards only 50c. World Office.\nSpecial for one week\u2014so calling!\ncards only 50c. World Office.\nAlbert Wh'tley, '*\\e aew jeweler. I\nWatches and clocks carefully re-j\npaired. Prices right. Shop in Mc-\nGohan's place. 3-12\nTHIRTY GENTS\nON EACH SHARE\ni-inal Dividend on Stock in Old Che\nlan C ounty Fair Associa\ntion.\nDid Walter Olive mail you a check j\nfor thirty cents?\nIf he did, this is his explanation:\nThe affairs of the defunct Chelan j\nCounty Fair Associa' ion have been I\nfinally wound up, and cliat was your\ndivvy as a stockholder\u20143o cents ft]\nshare.\nD. A. Beal wa? president and Wal\nter M. Olive secretary of the old j\norganization, which flourished herei\nin ante-boom days, and its stock was\nvalued at $10 per share. When it\nwent out of business in 1906 there\nwere funds on hands to pay all obli- I\ngations, and repay the stockholders\nIn full, plus a $2 per share bonus, j\nA small sum was left on deposit in\nthe Columbia Valley Bank to meet\nsuch hang-over accounts as might\ncome 'up.\nA balance of $110.13. remaining af\nter all known debts and expenses of,\nclosing up have been paid, is being\ndivided among the old stockholders, j\nat a pro rata of thirty cents a share. I\nThis is the last act of t,he Chelan I\nCounty Fair association, whose un\ntimely end is deeply mourned.\n1 Mrs. N. I. Neubauer returned yes\nI terday from a delightful visit of sev\neral weeks with friends in Portland\nand Seattle.\nj It is policy to eat at the Gem Cafe;\nyou get your moneys worth.***\nMeals like mother used to cook at\nthe Gem Cafe.***\nCOMES FROM A\ni HEATHEN LAND\nMissionary Institute at Presbyterian\nCharcb Tonight Brings Visitor\nFrom Farotf f.ina.\nA notable gathering for Weuat.-hee\nwill convene at the Presbyterian\n;church tonight. The patty of mis-l\nsi maries will arrive this afternoon\n.direct from Seattle, and the opening;\nsession of the institute will take place 1\nat 7:30 this evening. The meetings'\ntonight and tomorrow will be popular,\nand will be crammed full of just that.\ninformation regarding the Orient and j\nthe great mission fields which every i\nwell informed person will be glad to\nI seize upon. Miss Fraser will be one j\n|of the speakers tonight. This ins-,i\ntute is not conducted along denomina-1\ntional lines, but will be of help and\ninspiration to all.\nMr. William T. Ellis, the well-]\nknown Philadelphia journalist has j\njust returned from a world tour of;\nmissions, and declares that \"Missions,\n[are a man's job.\" The program for!\ntomorrow:\n9:30 a. m. Prayer and Scripture\nj Exposition. Matthew 28-18-20.\n9:4;. a. m. Missionary Address, j\ni 10:10 a. m. Mission study confer-\nence.\n10:40 a. m. Model mission study\nclasses, home and foreign.\n11:20 a. m. Missions and finance.'\n12:00 m. Adjournment.\n1:45 p. m. The Holy Spirit and\ni missions.\n2:15 p. m. Conferences on Young\ni oeople, women's societies, men and\nmissions.\nj 2:45 p. m. Mission study classes.\"\ni 3:45 p. m: What shall we do? j\n4:00 p. m. Missionary address.\n4:15 p. m. Children's service led\nIby Miss Fraser.\ni 6:00 p. m. Basket lunch at the\nManse, to which all are invited. At\nthis, Mr. Porter and Dr. Ghormley\n|ni;i make after dinner addresses to\nthe nun.\n7:30 p. m. (Closing service of the\n[institute, which Mr. Porter will\nrhoae attending the day sessions\njaf** r.lvise.l o bring ratebooks and\n[pencu to take notes.\nDry Flat echo*} house, Mr. Clark was\nI elected director, and Will Sanahop\nwas elected at the Beaver Creek,\ni school hour *:'or director in that di.s\n--\u2022ji.-'.\nW. B. E tea has erected a windmill\nComing, Thursday, March 12, \"The Dairy Homestead\"\n4\nby Cashmere Comedy Co. General Admission 50c.\nAnd 25c. Given Under Auspices of the M. W. A.\nand a fifty foot wooden tower.\nHenry Wolf and John Witte are\nin Spokane.\nSickness is quite prevalent. Adam\nOppel and his son, George, and Win\nfleld Doneen are recovering from\npneumonia; there are also several\ncases of tonsilities.\nThere is such a solid crust on the\nsnow that it will hold up an ordinary\nperson. >w\nA large crowd attended the admin\nistrator's sale of the property of the\nlate Malinda Showalter. Mr. Taylor,\nfrom Wenatehee, was auctioneer.\nGrow Whiskers for Prize.\nTroy, Idaho, March 9. \u2014With\nheavy penalties for breaking the\na;-:ieement, fifteen young men em\nployed in banks, stores and offices\nhave organized a \"mustache club.\"\nThe members bind themselves not\nto save the upper lip for a period of\nthree months. Violation of this\nagreement will be punished, it hav\ning been agreed that the guilty mem\nber shall be compelled to buy a $5\nhat for all the other members. The\nmembei making the poorest showing\nduring the three months will enter\ntain the club at a stag dinner. The\nmember showing the most luxuriant\nmustache will be given a handsome\npnte\nFIRE MENACES\nLOCAL SCHOOLS\nNo Escapes at All on Two Buildings.\n\u2014No Fire drill this\nYear.\nNearly one thousand children in\nj Wenatehee are exposed to the danger\nlof being burned alive, like the 160\ni who died awful deaths in Ohio last\nweek.\nOn the big Whitman school build\ning there are no fire escapes at all.\nand only two doors from which exit\ncan be made. \"And to get out of the\nbuilding through the east door,\" said\n1 one of the teachers yesterday, \"the\nI pupils would have to go through the\n[basement, past the furnace.\"\ni No means of escaping from possible\nare provided at the Lewis and\nI Clarke building.\nj TThe Stevens building is provided\nwith an inadequate escape on one\nside; only one proper landing is pro\nvided, the escape passing the other\nUrindowfl diagonally. It is so narrow\nand so high from the ground at the\nbottom that in the event of being\ncrowded by panic-stricken pupils\ngreat loss of life could be avoided\nonly by a miracle.\nWhat the Law Says.\nUnder an ordinance passed Nov. 20,\nI 1906, while H. C. Littlefield, now\nI clerk of the school board, was mayor\nof the city, all school houses, hotels,\n[lodging houses, etc., of two stories or\n[over, were ordered equipped with\nproper fire escapes. Just why this\nhas never been done does not appear.\nNo Fire Drill.\nFire drills have not been held in\nany of the city schools this year,\nthough at the Lewis-Clarke school,\nwhere only one of the rooms on the\nupper floor is occupied, the pupils are\nmarched out on signal when school is\ndismissed. Fire drill at the Whitman I\nschool was abandoned last spring. j\nLater:\u2014lt was reported to the\nWorld office that the FIRST FIRE\nDRILL OF THE YEAR was held at\nthe Stevens school today.\nThe Daily World i 3 reluctant to\ntake its stand in the ranks of chronic\nMuck-rakers, but it has the welfare\nof the whole community at heart.\nIt would be unfair, perhaps, to take\nany particular person to task for the\nlack of fire-escapes on the school\nbuildings, for the city is young, of\nmushroom growth, and its finances\nare not quite as stable as the Bank\nof England. And there have\nmany other urgent issues facing the\nschool board and demanding after.- i\nnon. But it would seem that in viev j\no' the drastic steps taken in so many\no;her American ciries that Wf>natel!\u00bbe\na so, warned by the terrible hole- I\neaust in the Ohio town, should taito\nprecautions. t\nfottaee Hotel, Too.\nIn passing it is pertinenr to and i\nrh;U the dangerous conditions long:\nexiting af the Cettage Hotel are it j\nconstant source of comment among;\nobservant people who know the dan-;\nger from fire in three-story frame\nbuildings. The awful catastrophe\nat Shelton las' September is still m I\nmind; in that case fire in a wooden j\nhotel building, without escapes, luirn-j\ned to death a long list of unforti:nate\nvictims.\nREAD\nTHE\nWANT\nADS.\nFIVE CENTS PERCOPY.\nTO FORM TAFT\nCLUB TONIGHT\nMeeting Called to Endorse Roosevelt\ni-nd Declare for Fat Man from\nCincinnati.\nWord has gone out to the faithful\nin Republican ranks that a mass\nmeeting will be held at 7:15 tonight\nlin the police court room in the city\ni hall, for the purpose of organizing\nj a Chelan County Auxiliary Taft club,\nto co-operate with the State League\nformed at Tacoma last Thursday\nnight.\nJi is expected that at tonight's\nmeeting a committee will be desig\nnated, who will draft satisfactory\nresolutions endorsing William H.\nTaft and his policies for president.\nA copy of these resolutions will\nthen be forwarded to Secretary Lem\non, of the State Taft League, at Seat\ntle..\nExpect Much Fruit.\nWalla Walla, March 8. \u2014More in\nterest is taken in fruit rasing by the\nfarmers of the Walla Walla valley\nI this year than ever before, and it is\nexpected that the output of fruit will\n!be the largest in the history of the\nvalley. Walla Walla now supports\none cannery, which was operated last\nseason, and the Blalock Fruit com\npany may start another on a smaller\nscale to handle their products.\nFruit was formerly \"raised here ia\nlarge quantities, but several years\nago the coddling moth and San Jose\ni scale came into the valley and many\norchards became affected. The far\nmers allowed this condition to con\ntinue, and no effort was made to\nstamp out the pests,\nj The state experiment station at\nPullman finally discovered how best\nIto fight the pests, and then sbme of\nI the farmers began trying to clear\ntheir orchards. Not knowing the\nbest way to apply the solution, not\nmuch good resulted until last year\nProf. A. L. Melander and R. E. Trum\nble. of the government experiment\nstation at Pullman, came to the val\nley and conducted scientific experi\nments on three orchards in this coun\nty. The trees were carefully sprayed\nand accurate figures kept. The re\nsults were surprising, and one man,\nj who objected strongly to the experi\nmenters practicing on his trees, apol\nogized afterwards and declared that\nhe was ahead about one thousand\ndollars as a result of the spraying.\nEDITOR fAL\nPostofttce Bather Shop Under New\nManagement.\nJ. E. Mills and F. W. Whalen of\nthis cily have purchased the P. O.\nBarber Shop located under the post\noffice, where they will be glad co\nsee their old friends and patrou3.\nThe abovenamed shop has first-class\nbathrooms in connection. The two\ngentlemen are well known in We\nnatehee and vicinity. 3-14\nSpecial for one week\u2014*so calling\ncards only 5 oc. World Office.\nMesdames M. E. Henry and Terjy\nRoss have issued invitations for cards\non Thursday afternoon.\nDo you want to sell quick\u2014adver\ntise in the Daily World.\nMrs. Kathryn McNernel returned\nthis morning from her usual weekly\nmusic instruction in Cashmere, where\nshe has a large class now preparing\nfor a concert to be given early la\nApril.\nIf you are not pickir g up some of\nI the bargains that are being adver\ni tised in each Issue of the Daily\ni World.\nJohn Mooney and family have\n'moved into the house lately occupied\nIby Harry Manchester, corner of First\nI street and Chelan avenue. While Mrs.\n[A. Courtway. who purchased Mr.\nMeOney's home property ia preparing\nto take possession today.\nBig Sacrifice Sale.\nPipe nnst be used, so get in on\nthe ground floor. While this salo\nlasts. S<-> Wenatehee Plumbing\nH'-aMng Co. Phon\u00ab 231.\u2022\u2022\u2022\nj Wenatehee Plumbing, and Heating\nCo. can save you money on pipe.\nPhone 251.***","height":"22449","width":"15681"}}
